{Mikhail Tal lived from 9 xi 1936 until 28 vi 1992. He had become world
champion in his great attacking style. A memorial tournament was held in his
hometown Riga from 12 until 24 iv 1995. It was the first Super Classic of the
Intel Grand Prix, organized by the PCA. The other events were Novgorod 1995
and Horgen 1995.   Eleven grandmasters participated. Shirov withdrew because
he needed a rest. The decided games have been selected.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3.
Nc3 Nc6 4. g3 e6 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 O-O 9. Nxd5 exd5 10.
dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 f6 12. Bd2 Bf5 13. Qb3 Bb6 14. Be3 Na5 $5 {
Known is the exchange of bishops.} 15. Qc3 (15. Bxb6 $5 Nxb3 16. Bxd8 Nxa1 17.
Be7 Rfe8 {brings no advantage (Kramnik).}) 15... Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Re8 17. Qc5 $5
b6 $5 18. Qb5 a6 19. Qa4 b5 20. Qf4 Be4 21. Rac1 Nc4 $2 ({Better is} 21... d4
$1 22. Rfd1 Nc6) 22. b3 Ne5 23. Nd4 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Qb6 25. Rfd1 Rad8 26. Qf5 $1
g6 27. Qc2 Rd7 28. h3 Kg7 29. Qc5 Qb7 30. Rc3 b4 31. Rc2 Ree7 32. Rdc1 h5 33.
Qc8 Qb6 34. e3 Rd8 $6 (34... Qd6 $1 35. Rc7 Rxc7 36. Rxc7 Rxc7 37. Qxc7+ Qxc7
38. Ne6+ Kf7 39. Nxc7 {costs a pawn.}) 35. Ne6+ $1 Qxe6 36. Qxd8 Nf7 37. Qc8
Qe4+ 38. Kg1 Ng5 39. Rc7 $1 Nf3+ 40. Kf1 Nh2+ 41. Ke2 {White wins.} (41. Ke2
Qf3+ 42. Ke1 Qh1+ 43. Kd2 Nf3+ 44. Kc2 $1 Nd4+ 45. Kb2 {
escapes from the checks (Kramnik).}) 1-0

